The Familiar in the New Anti-Semitism
Why do so many Holocaust survivors sense emerging threats to Judaism even before they become widely visible?
Because they know that seemingly "harmless" hints can turn into accusations and ultimately lead to discrimination that is then legally entrenched.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm because they know what is at stake.
By doing so, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean Marie Le Pen or other crass right-wing extremists in Europe cause difficulties.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" were often stepping stones for fascism or communism, without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we deal with people - with the "educated middle class" in connection with mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds one of that used by the stepping stones of these anti-democratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world - fortunately not yet, but these are the voices of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to Great Britain should be mentioned: Not long ago, he referred to Israel during a dinner party in London as "this fucking little country."
His vulgar language is not particularly alarming.
More concerning are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the government demand Blair's recall. The matter was dismissed as just another scandal in public.
The French press portrayed the ambassador as a victim of British micro-media rather than of his own despicable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to Great Britain has several allies among Europe's elites.
Ambassador Bernard, however, rendered us a service: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish resentments are.
As a columnist put it so aptly: Israel has become an object of hatred whose name one dares not utter.
We must not only dare to say it, we are even obligated to speak it out.
Given the context and summaries provided, the translation of the German source sentence is:
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Antisemitic attacks are also reported from other places, such as Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the denial of the Holocaust becoming commonplace. Similarly, we must not remain silent about the comparisons antisemites and anti-Zionists draw between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Palestinian television portrays Israeli soldiers as rapists and cold-blooded murderers, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel."
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It is not my fault that Hitler hated the Jews. One almost hates them everywhere."
During the live broadcast of a Friday prayer on Palestinian television, the preacher called on Muslims to "show no mercy to the Jews. No matter where you are, kill them and these Americans who are just like them."
What we should think about in the context of antisemitism is that it always begins with the Jews, but never ends with the Jews.
If anti-Semitism is not contained, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against antisemitism is therefore the task of Jews as much as non-Jews.
Currently, the attack points in this struggle are blurrier than ever before, as a remarkable aspect of contemporary antisemitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of antisemitism remains the same - to attack the Jews - it still changes its appearance, strategy, rationalizations, and even its vocabulary.
Once, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this was not accepted, the Jews were expelled or killed.
When racial theory captivated people in the 19th century, the Jews were attacked because of their affiliation with a wicked race.
With the existence of the state of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, today Zionism is slandered as a racist ideology.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with antisemitism.
It is equally legitimate to critically stand opposed to certain political strategies and decisions made by Israel, just as it is with other nations.
The anti-Zionism is becoming increasingly similar to antisemitism.
Anti-Zionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of Great Britain, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
They would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people but hate their state.
And yet, there are people in the context of Israel who claim to be able to do exactly that.
In various UN organizations, insults directed at Israel are on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state entity in the Middle East is a key aspect of this new antisemitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil," then, as Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament, puts it, the "lesson of contempt" circulates within the UN.
This constant portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is in reality a campaign against the Jewish people.
So the numerous anti-Jewish attacks in many countries are rooted in the demonizations of Israel that employ antisemitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this slanderous language in connection with the Middle East.
Compared to earlier anti-Jewish outbursts, today's antisemitism is less about attacks on individual Jews, but rather an attack on the "collective Jew," namely the State of Israel.
Such attacks have set off a chain reaction of assaults on individual Jews and Jewish institutions throughout Europe and Latin America.
Earlier, the most dangerous antisemites were those who wanted to make the world judenrein.
The most dangerous antisemites of today are those who want to make the world judenstaatrein.
